{meta: title Grandma Harp}
{meta: artist Merle Haggard}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]Grandma's maiden [F]name was Zona [C]Villines
And there's ninety years to tell about in a [G7]few short lines
[C]Born in Newton [F]County down in [C]Arkansas
Then [D7]in 1901 she married [G7]grandpa
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
We [C]laid her soul to [F]rest one Sunday [C]morning
And everybody [F]knew she'd done her [C]part
Don't get set to hear no [F]hidden family [C]legend [A7]
Just a [D7]song about the [G7]life of Grandma [C]Harp
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Just think [F]about the [C]times that she lived through
And to think about the changin' [G7]world she saw
[C]Now some how [F]she reared a decent [C]family out of poverty
[D7]And for seventy years she loved the [G7]same ole grandpa
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[C]To me her [F]passin' brought a closin' [C]chapter
To a way of life that [F]I loved within my [C]heart
I just mean to say I think we [F]owe her something [C]special[A7]
If just a [D7]song about the [G7]life of Grandma [C]Harp
{end_of_verse}

